A big return for the Czech loser is approaching.
Pavel Francouz has been called up to the NHL
Czech ice hockey goaltender Pavel Francouz, who is going through a difficult period in his career, is returning to the NHL.
The 31-year-old native of Pilsen will be on the bench and could soon find himself in goal.
The former Litvínov, Plzeň and Russian Chelyabinsk goalkeeper was injured during preparation for the NHL in October this year.
He was subbed out in the middle of the game against Vegas and has not played in the NHL since.
The incident occurred as the experienced goalkeeper moved from one post to the other.
"Pavel Francouz will be out approximately three to four weeks with a lower-body injury," the Avalanche announced in early October.
His return to the NHL net ended up lasting more than two months.
Called up from the farm on Sunday morning U.S. time, he threw four innings and showed his old form.
In the AHL, he recorded 94.5% of his saves.
The former Plzeň hockey player wants to finally make it and prove that he belongs in the best league in the world.
In the last season, he had problems with his hip and in the shortened pandemic season, he didn't play a single game.
In the NHL, "Francík" played 36 matches, his success rate is 92.3%.
