According to efotbal.cz, Slavia promised Berbr a million for the title. Tvrdík denied this.
Prague - The investigators in the current corruption case reportedly worked with the assumption that the accused former vice-president of the Football Association of the Czech Republic, Roman Berbr, had been promised one million Czech crowns from the Prague Slavia for the league title in the 2018/19 season.
The efotbal.cz website reported this, adding that it had access to part of the police files.
The chairman of the board of the Vršovice club, Jaroslav Tvrdík, stated that the red-and-whites did not engage in any corruption.
The server published a transcript of the police wiretaps, in which Slavia is mainly represented by its former sports director Jan Nezmar, who left the club last summer.
According to the indictment, the former influential official of the red-and-whites was in frequent contact with Berbr, as well as with the former sports director of the then second-league Vyšehrad Roman Rogoz, who is also among the accused in the case.
The detectives were reportedly working with information that Slavia had promised Berbatov a financial reward for winning the title.
In 2019, the SK Slavia Prague team won the first league title.
The police authority was in possession of the knowledge that Roman (Berbr) was promised a million-crown bribe from the officials of SK Slavia Prague for winning the league, the server cited from the file.
The following day, according to the police, Berbr met not only with Nezmara, but also with the chairman of Slavia's board of directors, Tvrdík.
According to the server, it is not clear from the file whether the police are still dealing with this information.
Tvrdík has denied any corruption.
Between 2015 and 2017, we actively tried to change the situation in Czech football and we offered an alternative to its development.
We have never committed an illegal act, we have not tried to influence the referees in violation of the fair play rules, and we have not provided anyone with any financial compensation in connection with this," Tvrdík told Seznam Zprávy.
In the recordings, Nezmar, among other things, indiscriminately insults some former dark-skinned Slavia players and also slanders his former boss, Tvrdík.
The case of alleged match-fixing through referees was sparked by a police raid in mid-October last year, at several locations including the headquarters of the FAČR in Prague.
Berbr is the highest-ranking person involved in the affair, who no longer holds any football positions.
Like former Vyšehrad sports director Rogoz, he was released from custody in mid-January.
Helicopters, tanks, and BVPs are LARPing the Cold War.
The tanks will be new, but essentially of a worse type (the gunners will have to fire from an armoured cabin and carry ammunition by hand without cover).
The vehicles - Toyota Hi-luxes - are new and good
Trucks and various armoured vehicles - at a decent level, moreover, it has managed to get rid of the Praga V3S in specialist units.
Aircraft: combat - decent, but at the end of the lease, transport - too small with a short range, but modern.
Drones - few and small types with no combat potential
Rockets - we don't have any at all (but we manufacture them and export them overseas)
NGO: medium - cold war, obsolete; short range - good, modern, relatively good numbers.
I have a story.
My hunting grounds are right next to the city.
The nutria were coming out of the river and causing damage to the crops, so I sat there.
When I arrived, I saw that there was a fisherman on the other side of the river.
I didn't want to make a scene, so I sat down quietly and the guy probably didn't notice me.
I was hoping that he would leave before something came out, but of course the fox was soon out of the henhouse.
I let her get to 40 metres before I decided to shoot.
The poor fisherman nearly had a heart attack, he was waving his torch all over the place, so I called out to him that it was a fox.
By the time I got off the bench, I was livid.
That is to say, a man can be a prat.
On the other hand, it's not war, it would have to be a series of coincidences for something to happen, you'd probably be seen on a thermal imaging camera, which almost everyone has today.
So put your valuables in a visible place, put them in your sleeping bag, and you should be fine.
