The Ministry of the Interior procured respirators much more cheaply than the Ministry of Health
The state, responsible for purchasing and distributing face masks, masks and respirators for professions closest to the coronavirus, has spent billions of crowns on their purchase in recent weeks.
The iRozhlas server compared the purchases of individual ministries and found that the prices of respirators differed by hundreds of crowns on a single day.
Why did the prices fluctuate so dramatically?
Which authorities have been frugal?
And why did others buy at a higher price?
Lenka Kabrhelová speaks to iRozhlas editor Dominika Kubištová.
I respect the soldiers and the army (I am probably not affected by the memories of the former Czechoslovak Army, which the older generations went through), but the Czech Republic cannot benefit from compulsory military service.
We don't even have large stockpiles of equipment that reservists could pick up, we don't even have modern equipment for the current professionals, and on top of that modern equipment is getting more and more complicated, so the reservists' skills will rapidly decline over time.
On top of that, modern conventional conflicts, where anyone can be deployed, will play out very quickly, there will be no time to retrain someone.
And finally, the reserves/territorial defense have a big role to play in countries like Ukraine, where leading a mass guerrilla war is a stated necessity to deter the enemy.
In the territory of the Czech Republic, it will only be possible to fight in a conflict of such a scale and intensity that the guerrilla will be irrelevant, and we do not have the right geography for that.
Mainly, we don't have individual skills.
This is not even the worst of it.
The worst thing is that half of them play like they have it.
Then comes a situation where you look like an idiot, who 2 minutes ago didn't hit an empty net, drives into the attack alone between 2 or even 3 Swiss players, and you ask yourself "what do you think is going to happen now?"
Of course, they're going to treat him like an average taxpayer.
The situation with this skill "to take on a defender" is so bad that I caught myself being genuinely surprised when I saw that our attacker managed to beat one of the opponent's players.
First signs
The Covid-19 pandemic is slowing down, but experts do not expect any major developments in the coming weeks.
The pressure on hospitals will continue for some time, according to statistical models, and a new unknown has been added to the pandemic equation: the omicron variant, which is very likely to spread faster than the currently dominant Delta.
At the same time, it is not yet possible to say with absolute certainty whether it can cause a more serious course of the disease, or to what extent vaccination or post-infection immunity acquired from a previous infection helps against it.
This week, however, an unexpected phenomenon on the plus side has entered the covid equation: the possibility of treatment.
A new drug has arrived in the Czech Republic, the antiviral molnupiravir, which reduces the risk of a severe course of the disease and associated hospitalisation by a third, and can be taken at home.
Soon it will be joined by the Pfizer drug paxlovid, which, according to preliminary results, is successful in up to 85 percent of cases.
The first deliveries of molnupiravir to the Czech Republic, in addition to the hope of expanding the portfolio of useful tools in the fight against the coronavirus pandemic, have also highlighted the question of how the Czech administration is prepared for incoming drugs.
As mentioned, the first drug to reach Czech patients will be molnupiravir by Merck.
The company ended up on the tape first because the drug was being developed long before the current pandemic to find a suitable treatment for a viral disease in horses on the South American continent.
What is often overlooked in these studies is that people in the West (Germany, Sweden, etc.)
are generally less open and do not openly share their opinions.
On the other hand, Eastern Europeans, and especially we Czechs, are used to saying "as if a beak had grown on our noses".
So you do research where you ask people if they like Muslims.
In the Czech Republic, most people will tell you straight up that they don't.
In the West, they will tell you how much they like migration, how we should all help them, and how we Czechs are racist pigs.
And then they go and vote for parties like the AfD.
They fear cancel culture, saying this in public means losing your job and media lynching.
Then it looks nice in the polls, West good, East bad.
But they will find out what people really think.
