It is funny that the USSR did not want to have nuclear warheads on its own territory, either for security reasons or because of the speed of deployment of the warheads due to its more western location.
Only the warheads were stored in the underground bunkers (there were two in each maple tree), not the entire missiles.
If it was necessary to use this weapon, a special unit would arrive, pick up the head and mount it on some kind of carrier.
Aside from the museum sycamore, the rest are in a state of disrepair.
At the second stage of elementary school, we had a Gypsy classmate, and we were together for 4 years.
He was pretty good, he made some good jokes, he was a bit over the top, but he was like our mascot.
Everyone talked to him, he often came and wanted to explain something, he was almost always here, he did sports with us, he didn't steal our snacks or phones, he came dressed properly.
He also went on nature schools, did all kinds of monkey business, but he was fine, probably never got into any trouble.
In the eighth or ninth grade, the siblings entered the same grade, different classes.
Shortly thereafter, they beat up a teacher, the police were often called there, they threatened and intimidated other students...
I personally sometimes sell something on a classified ad (old things, things I don't need, etc.) and I've sold to Gypsies many times, they always had money, they didn't try to trick me out of the price, the communication was calm.
I have even sold a car this way, a guy called me a month later, saying that he had already transferred it to himself...
I say to myself that I'm not a racist, I don't care if someone is white, black, yellow, blue or any other colour, as long as they behave as they should in decent society (works, functions, doesn't beat women, just normal behaviour).
But as soon as someone comes, stretches out their hand, evicts flats and houses, has a mess around them and causes problems... it doesn't matter what colour they are, but it will bother me.
I have no problem with African migrants if they integrate here, start a business, work, learn the language (not necessarily, at least English), and respect our culture.
If they believe in Allah, I don't care, as long as they respect my traditions and culture, I will respect theirs.
A young woman died in a car crash in Prachatice
"The young woman suffered multiple serious injuries and despite resuscitation efforts, she unfortunately died from her injuries at the scene," the spokesperson for the South Bohemian ambulance service, Zuzana Fajtlová, told Právo.
The accident was probably caused by the driver who was transporting the girl.
The 18-year-old driver of the Peugeot was probably driving from the village of Žíchovec to the village of Bavorov and, for unknown reasons, left the road in a bend.
After the collision with the Skoda Octavia, the Peugeot ended up on its roof off the road, said South Bohemian police spokeswoman Štěpánka Schwarzová.
The young Peugeot driver suffered very serious injuries in the accident.
It was multiple injuries and he was trapped in the car.
After being freed, he had to be provided with emergency pre-hospital care, and was airlifted to the hospital in České Budějovice in a stable condition, said rescuer Fajtlová.
She added that the man in the second car suffered a minor chest injury and was taken to hospital.
New rules apply to parcels from outside the EU, customers often fail to provide information about them
Lukáš Neuheisl orders from abroad several times a month.
He mainly gets collector's cards.
"Usually it can be dozens of dollars, say, from ten dollars or more, where it is still worthwhile to import, especially from Japan, where postage is often free," says the collector.
Since October, ordering small packages has become slightly more expensive; he now has to add VAT and give customs information to the post office.
He will receive an e-mail stating that customs are awaiting the arrival of the package.
Then you just have to fill in the information about the shipment, and if the seller did not include VAT in the sale, the customs office will collect it from the total amount of the shipment and transport.
If the recipient does not take care of customs procedures themselves, they must add the carrier's fee to the total amount.
According to Lukáš Neuheisl, however, the whole process is not complicated.
I check one or two boxes, add two attachments, and I'm done.
For me, it's usually a matter of five minutes, says Neuheisl.
Not all deliveries go smoothly though.
Due to new customs regulations, the daily number of parcels received from abroad at the international post office in Prague fell from 60,000 to 15,000.
According to the Czech Post Office, the problem is also that people do not react to calls to submit information necessary to complete the customs procedure.
Currently, there are 30,000 parcels awaiting processing at the international post office.
If people were to fill in all the information that is required and fill it in on time, we would be about halfway there, says Matyáš Vitík, spokesman for the Czech Post.
