Christmas book tips
The Christmas double issue, published on 20 December, will include the traditional literary supplement.
And along with it, cultural tips.
We are also including the books for you, our subscribers, with this digital edition, so that you have enough time to buy the books as Christmas presents.
The prose texts follow on from the previous similar collection Petříček Sellier & Petříček Bellot.
Another helping of observations of the world and descriptions of ordinary things with an extraordinary poetic attention to detail, depth, and atmosphere.
In his second novel, the photographer Šesták tried to capture the essence of a small town and the Czech society.
A story of a return to roots that will turn out to be nothing more than a longed-for illusion.
The Bohemist and comparatist transfers the fairy tale of Little Red Riding Hood to the backdrop of a contemporary village.
Its delivery of brutality surpasses the folk versions and escalates into a horror of emotional emptiness.
And that the path back to instincts is shorter than we are willing to admit
The author's penultimate novel tells a far less sentimental story about returning from emigration than we are used to hearing.
Those who stayed and those who left know too little about each other to make it work.
Trains start running according to new timetable, some operators change
From Sunday, trains will be running according to a new timetable.
The biggest change is the replacement of carriers on some routes, for example between Ústí nad Labem and Kolín, where instead of Czech Railways, RegioJet starts running.
For most lines, only the departure times will be adjusted, and in some cases their routes will be adjusted slightly.
There will also be dozens of new trains on the tracks.
Transport companies started selling tickets during the autumn.
České dráhy plan to operate an average of 6,783 passenger services daily in the new timetable, of which an average of 478 will be long-distance trains.
The trains will travel approximately 118 million kilometres during the new timetable.
In addition to domestic connections, the new timetable will also include routes to Germany, Poland, Slovakia, Hungary, Austria and Switzerland.
The company will introduce dozens of new trains along with the new timetable.
The main innovation will be the InterJet trains, which will travel on routes from Prague to Cheb.
The transport company will also run new trains in northern Moravia and western Bohemia.
The transport company will also traditionally increase the price of tickets next year, by an average of 3.2 percent.
The railways factor in inflation into their tariffs every year.
The biggest change in the RegioJet timetable is the introduction of the R23 Ústí nad Labem – Mělník – Nymburk – Kolín line.
The transport company will replace České dráhy here after its success in the Ministry of Transport competition.
RegioJet will operate a total of 16 trains a day on the line, eight in each direction.
Other changes affect long-distance trains between Prague and Brno, which from Sunday will also stop at Havlíčkův Brod, Žďár nad Sázavou and Kolín stations.
Leo Express has kept its 16 connections, two return connections to Slovakia and also weekend connections to Krakow.
According to spokesman Emil Sedlařík, the transport company also tried to keep the schedules of its long-distance trains as similar as possible despite the planned maintenance work.
The operations of Arriva trains and other carriers should continue without major changes.
Transport operators will change in some regional lines.
There will be changes for passengers, for example in the Liberec region, where instead of Czech Railways, the Trilex trains of the German company Die Länderbahn will run on the line from Mladá Boleslav via Česká Lípa to Rumburk.
In the second year, travellers will also be able to use a unified ticket for the railways.
Just like Czech Railways, their price will increase by inflation of 3.2 per cent.
I have to disagree.
Don't we learn from the other side's perspective?
We hear everywhere how much they had to struggle for their rights, how they were oppressed and had to work hard and die.
In my life, I've never heard a lesson from the perspective of the slave-owner's side or from that time, no one is defending it, just condemning it.
No one tells you in school that black people often sold other black people into slavery and that they were often the worst slavers.
No one will teach you in school that the colonisers often bought the land from the Indians. They will only tell you how brutally we, the Europeans, wiped them out, when in fact, they had been killing each other for a long time.
I also spent some time in the USA, directly in the schools, both in the northern and the southern schools.
I haven't come across anyone deliberately covering up facts, but I have heard of it happening in the past, and I think it's a problem, which I don't deny (for example, WW2 atrocities are quite a taboo in Japan).
My point was rather that history is not black and white and that we tend to look at it from today's perspective, without understanding.
History is not interested in people's feelings, it is just what it is, and I think it is a fatal mistake to condemn without looking at things from the time.
On the other hand, we should learn from it and never do it again.
By the way, while we're on the subject of the southern states, yes, the Confederate flag and the famous slave owners are quite popular there, on the other hand, they also had some good successes and it seemed absurd to me to reject them.
In addition, the North was not much better, as many people idealise it today.
And a lot of people also forget that not everyone in the South were slave owners and a lot of things also went against them.
I wouldn't compare this to the Russians, they deliberately leave out some facts, lie and manipulate, moreover, our point of view doesn't exist for them (there was a video on YT from the television, where they turned off someone who started talking about our legionnaires and 1968).
What I found funny about US schools was the rise of Marxism and the idealisation of communism, something their country has never experienced.
Overall, it seemed to me that at some universities it was terrible, those students were quite radicalised and those schools often supported them.
