The flame from Bethlehem is in the Czech Republic, scouts took it over from Austria
Břeclav – The flame lit in Bethlehem, where according to Christian tradition Jesus Christ was born, is in the Czech Republic.
However, due to the coronavirus pandemic, the scouts did not travel to Vienna for him this time. In the morning, they received him from their Austrian colleagues at the Reintal - Břeclav border crossing.
Last year, they also took it at the border.
The Bethlehem Light is a beautiful Christmas tradition that we participate in every year with the group, and I really look forward to it.
It is an honour for me that I have been chosen, said the scout Amálie Budíková to the present journalists.
While last year the handover took place at the Mikulov-Drasenhofen border crossing, directly on the border bridge, this year it took place at the Reintal-Břeclav border crossing on the car park.
However, the scouts usually travel to Vienna by train.
Nothing changes in the delivery of the flame across the Czech Republic.
The scouts set off with the Bethlehem light by train to Brno, where they will hand it over to the diocesan bishop, Vojtěch Cikrle.
On Saturday, 18 December, scout couriers will take care of the subsequent distribution of the light. They will travel by selected express trains and passenger trains.
The light will be taken over by local scouts and volunteers, who will then spread the flame across the Czech Republic to places where the tracks do not lead.
This year too, the scouts must follow the current measures against the spread of the coronavirus.
It's going the same way as last year.
We recommend both the delivery teams and organisers of local events to, of course, wear masks, try to keep a safe distance, be as few as possible, not to sing to each other, just to behave so that it is as safe as possible, described the spokesperson of the Bethlehem Light event, Zuzana Hrbková.
The tradition of the Bethlehem light traveling through Europe was born in 1986 in Austria.
The aim is to spread the idea of peace, friendship and peace along with the flame.
For believers, the Bethlehem light is a symbol of hope, a light that overcomes the darkness.
In the Czech Republic, the Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts have been involved in its dissemination for more than 30 years.
Hundreds of volunteers are involved in the event, and the flame is also a symbol of selflessness and human solidarity.
All the news, including a list of places where people can come for the flame, can be found on the website www.betlemskesvetlo.cz.
