TV has fallen out of love with the Christmas movie, with two hundred premiering this year
Los Angeles - Movie theaters, TV channels and streaming platforms in the United States and other English-speaking countries are bucking the trend of Christmas films and are premiering more than 200 this year.
The operator of the IMDb film database did the count.
The genre of Christmas family and romantic films has been scoring with the audience in recent years and has significantly increased viewership, so more and more of these films are being made.
Four times as many Christmas films were made this year than in 2011 and twice as many as five years ago.
The IMDb database only includes those films that have the word Christmas in their title, so there are actually a lot more Christmas films out there.
Films that people traditionally associate with Christmas have always been there.
In the Czech Republic, this period is mainly associated with fairy tales; worldwide, the films Home Alone, Love Actually and the classic Christmas story It's a Wonderful Life from 1946 are popular.
However, the real boom in Christmas movies started in 2009, when the American cable television channel Hallmark came up with a special film series, the BBC website recalled.
Her Advent project called Countdown to Christmas then included four films and was very successful.
This year, the channel started to tune in its viewers for Christmas on 22 October and will show a total of 42 Christmas films.
Competitor network Lifetime has 35 new Christmas-themed films on its schedule this year, and popular streaming platforms like Netflix are also contributing to the total.
"In this magical time of year, the story doesn't matter as much as the fact that there's a lot of Christmas trees in the background and it's snowing," Brandon Gray, author of the book "I'll Be Home for Christmas Movies," said with a laugh.
"For the audience, it's a form of escape and a way to at least for two hours feel a little bit of calm in the midst of all of the holiday craziness and the craziness of the world we've been living in for the last few years," Gray added.
According to him, for example, the Hallmark channel uses the same recipe for its films, which is uniform, but successful.
You have two people falling in love, but then there's a misunderstanding about half an hour before the end, which is successfully resolved and the two people kiss.
That's just the way it is, and as long as all the films look the same and have the same atmosphere, people will watch one after the other, adds Gray.
