California will limit gun sales.
They want to follow Texas' lead in banning abortions.
California Gov. Gavin Newsom on Saturday announced a plan to ban the sale and manufacture of some guns in the nation's most populous state through a legal mechanism used by Texas in its controversial abortion law that bans the procedure once a fetal heartbeat is detected.
People would then have the right to sue anyone in California who manufactures or sells assault weapons and homemade guns.
Newsom's announcement came in response to a ruling by the U.S. Supreme Court on Friday that left in place a Texas law that bans abortions after about six weeks of pregnancy, despite being at odds with a nearly 50-year-old precedent that established a nationwide right to abortion until about the 24th week of pregnancy.
The court was not, however, ruling on the constitutionality of the whole law, but on a technical issue arising from the innovative construction of the measure.
Enforcement of the ban was turned over to the public in this case, making it impossible for Texas Republicans to challenge it in court.
"I am outraged by yesterday's (Friday) decision by the U.S. Supreme Court to uphold Texas' ban on most abortions and largely endorse Texas' scheme to shield its law," the California governor said.
"If states can now block the review of their laws by federal courts, then California will use that authority to protect human lives," Newsom continued.
He allegedly instructed his subordinates to work with the state parliament and the minister of justice on a measure that would allow public representatives to enforce a ban on assault rifles and so-called ghost guns.
So-called "ghost guns" are homemade guns that don't have serial numbers and can be used to evade regulations.
Newsom wants "private citizens" to have the right to sue for at least $10,000 (220,000 CZK) in damages and legal fees from anyone who manufactures, distributes or sells assault rifles, "ghost gun" parts or kits to make them in California.
"If the most effective way to keep these deadly weapons off our streets is to create a threat of private lawsuits, then that's exactly what we should do," the California governor said.
The AP notes that California has banned the manufacture and sale of some military-style weapons for decades, but a federal judge in June blocked the ban as unconstitutional.
If the state were to actually reinstate the ban using the Texas model, it would confirm the words of liberal Supreme Court Justice Sonia Sotomayor, who in a dissenting opinion to Friday's majority ruling warned against expanding the legal mechanism to other U.S. states.
The Supreme Court, however, did not grant Texas's ban on abortion total immunity from judicial review, allowing abortion clinics to continue their lawsuits against certain officials in the southern U.S. state.
