As a child, I was punished with a wooden spoon.
It was never because of grades, it was just that I repeatedly refused to listen and misbehaved (reading instead of going to bed, fighting with my brother, etc).
At the same time, I have never been punished without a warning. My mother would always first threaten that if I did it again, I would get a slap (sometimes even after "catching" the spoon a second time, she would just bring it and place it so that I could see it).
It wasn't until I repeatedly refused to listen that I received a couple of slaps to the backside (through clothing).
Personally, I believe that physical punishment (in a reasonable manner and amount) is beneficial, as a child responds to it much more than words.
I think the part with the warning is important, because it gives the child a choice whether to disobey and get the punishment, or to improve and not get the punishment.
I usually just needed a warning to start listening.
Defending the system
When the prominent Czech lawyer and constitutional judge Vojtěch Cepl answered a journalist's question in 1999 on what the Czech constitution means to him - whether it is a sacred document to which one swears an oath and which is taught at school from an early age, or, on the contrary, an agreement that can be changed if necessary - he definitely favoured the first option.
We once agreed in the constitution on the democratic rules of our lives, which at the same time define who we are as a state and its citizens, and we should be more careful with changes.
And imagine this: some nations actually like their rules.
Just like Czechs love dumplings with pork and sauerkraut, Vojtěch Cepl remarked at the time.
However, in recent times, it has become more common for lawyers to argue that the Czech Constitution needs to be changed.
For years, it has been tested by situations that its creators (including Vojtěch Cepl) could not predict, such as the behaviour of the directly elected president.
One thing Cepl was right about, though.
Everything we know about such documents suggests that political interventions in their text must be well thought out.
The institution must be understood and actively defended, only then can it be the key to dealing with most of the crises that societies have faced throughout history.
The constitution, among other things, is a set of rules of government that set limits on what politicians can do.
We fear that power will be abused against minorities or individuals, so we tie the hands of politicians with bans.
At the same time, the constitutional texts also allow politicians to exercise their power.
Covid-19 doesn't discriminate; a six-month-old baby is fighting for its life at the Brno University Hospital
Although it is known that the coronavirus is usually milder for children, there are also severe cases, which the hospital has mainly been dealing with in recent times.
"We know that children are less at risk and less affected than adults, with 2 to 5 percent compared to adults," said Petr Dominik, head of the Department of Paediatric Anesthesiology and Resuscitation at the University Hospital Brno and the Medical Faculty of Masaryk University to Novinky.
The course is much easier, milder, often without symptoms.
There are, however, child patients who are severely ill with the coronavirus, which we can see in particular in recent times," added Dominik.
According to the doctor, there are dozens of children who need mild supportive care.
It is set in a children's infectious disease clinic.
Children who are very seriously ill with coronavirus have only recently been admitted to PICU.
According to the doctor, children with post-Covid syndromes have been admitted to the department continuously throughout the year.
"Now we're seeing an increase in kids with acute COVID pneumonia, that's the inflammation of the lungs that requires admission to the intensive care unit," he said, adding that the illness affects not just adults but also adolescents and infants as young as a few months old.
There are also children in critical condition due to COVID-19 in hospitals.
"Currently, we have a child of several months and an adolescent in our care," said the chief physician.
However, she is happy that, so far, there have been no child deaths in the children's hospital at the Brno University Hospital due to the coronavirus.
According to available data, six children aged between 0 and 14 died in the Czech Republic on 6 December.
According to Dominik, in a children's hospital - not just in the COVID-19 ward - a psychologist is an integral part of the team.
At the same time, he points out that, just like in adults, vaccination reduces the severity of the disease and at the same time reduces the incidence of the post-Covid syndrome in children.
"That's why we recommend the vaccination for children as well," added the doctor.
