Kara-France then took care of Cody Garbrandt.
In the spring, Nunes celebrated another triumph with her little daughter, now, after seven years, she has lost.
That hip or that hip?
At first glance, it doesn't seem complicated.
Most nouns in Czech express only one grammatical gender, so there is no problem in determining whether they are masculine, feminine or neuter.
Then there is also a fairly large group of nouns for which the gender is not fixed.
Such substantive nouns oscillate between two genders.
When inflected, they acquire dual endings, and in some cases remain in the uninflected form.
For example, the words "svízel" and "kyčel" are both masculine and feminine, in the first one they are declined according to the pattern "stroj", in the second one according to the pattern "píseň".
Another group of nouns have different forms in the first singular case, for example: "řádek/řádka", "kedluben/kedlubna" or "brambor/brambora" (in the sense of food).
Both forms are correct, have the same meaning, and are therefore freely interchangeable.
Some words can vary regionally, for example "okurka" in Bohemia and "okurek" in Moravia, in this case the Moravian variant is non-standard, as is the case with other Czech-Moravian pairs of words: "příkop" and "příkopa", "kobliha" and "koblih", etc.
Some words that have entered the Czech language from other languages were originally uninflected, but have gradually adopted Czech endings.
A typical example is the word "image", which is of both masculine and feminine gender, or the word "buffet", which remains in the middle gender without declension, but in masculine it has endings according to the model of "castle".
