How the pandemic has changed our love lives: Number of under-35s going a year without sex soars
More and more young adults in the U.S. are living their lives without sex.
This is mainly religious people, says the website of the DailyMail newspaper.
The survey showed that between 2008 and 2021, the proportion of people under 35 who abstain from sex increased from eight to 21 per cent.
The number of women aged between 18 and 35 who said they have not had sex in the past year is at an all-time high.
The decline in the number of sexually active individuals is due to other factors, according to a survey by the Institute for Family Studies (IFS).
One of them could be the economic impact of the coronavirus pandemic and a higher unemployment rate.
However, the presence of the media, social networks or video games could also have played a part, making sex less of a priority for young people.
"From 2010, there has been a rapid increase in the share of men and women aged 18 to 35 who say they have not had sex in the past year," said IFS researcher Lyman Stone.
Those in married relationships are more sexually active, with just 5 per cent saying they had gone a year without sex in 2021.
Among the never-married, it was 29 percent. Stone added that marriages under the age of 35 are only a small percentage.
The decline in sexual activity is also due to the fear of premarital sex and religious background.
While married couples are more likely to be sexually active, the percentage of married and cohabiting men and women under 35 is still falling.
Young people are divided on premarital sex, with about 30% thinking it's a bad thing and about 70% thinking it's OK.
"It's true that they're a minority among free-living individuals in this age group, but their behavior is driving this trend," Stone said of the 30 percent.
Most of those who have a moral problem with premarital sex do so on religious grounds.
From 2008 to 2018, the rate of abstinence among unmarried people younger than 35 who attend religious services more than once a month rose from 20 percent to nearly 60 percent.
Among the "less religious," the trend rose from 10 to 20 percent," Stone said.
Other factors also contribute to the decline in sexual activity, such as less social interaction and especially social drinking during the pandemic.
The study also found that people who are unemployed or have lower incomes are less likely to have sex.
Another reason could be the expansion of digital media, which seems to reduce the need for sex.
People are spending more time online, which is "substituting" for this need.
This trend has taken hold mainly during the lockdown in the time of the coronavirus pandemic.
The whole issue of vaccinating against Covid is whether a society should force part of its population to do something they don't want to do, but which may save their lives.
It's a pretty tough question, and the one I'm personally most interested in is the question of the social conscience.
That is to say, for example, the question of whether if we don't order them to do it and they die, it will be our fault.
My argument is that we could certainly be held responsible for the death of an 80-year-old man who really didn't know what he was doing, we didn't explain it well enough to him, he heard some misinformation, and as a result, he didn't get vaccinated and eventually caught it and died.
On the other hand, I don't think we can be held responsible for the death of a stubborn opponent of vaccinations, who is standing here next to the SPD and the KSČ, shouting something about bullying and a totalitarian state.
From those statistics I mentioned, it is quite clear that the majority of unvaccinated pensioners probably belong to the second group, so they will be able to blame themselves for it.
