Dog Hugo is doing what he can.
But Juraj Šajmovič did not keep an eye on his film.
Czech creators of family comedies have taken a liking to American stories about beloved pets.
But they forgot one important thing: the laws of filmmaking.
After the kitsch film F. Brabec's Gump - the dog who taught people to live, another film, Tady hlídáme my, is now competing for audience emotions in cinemas.
The film's co-screenwriter and director, Juraj Šajmovič jr., loosely follows his previous film Tady hlídám já from 2012.
The talking hedgehog Hugo returns to the scene, along with some of the familiar characters around him.
Julie and Ivan, the owners of a Šumava pension that is dying and so they start to invite dog owners, Julie's father with his partner and especially her daughter Veronika.
She is no longer a little girl but a young woman experiencing her first love.
The director and his partner, Beatriz Šajmovičová (who is also the film's producer), struggled with the storytelling in their previous dog film, but at least children and the dog were entertaining.
This time, the creative duo has written an even weaker script, which elicits a mixture of awe and feelings of embarrassment.
Let's recap.
Julie, despite being a scientist, succumbs to the darkness of her desire for a child and, when the "constellations" are right, copulates with her forest engineer, Ivan, wherever the coordinates indicate - on the bonnet of a car or a church tower (of course, during an ongoing tour with a local guide), the retired Colonel Mojmír, despite years of training, shoots his own daughter (Julie) in the forest, who falls into a coma, after which she is taken from the hospital by the family to undergo a miraculous healing process with a dog in the heart of the Šumava wilderness.
Nothing wrong with the restorative powers of nature and the strength of animal companions.
Their owners know why they have them.
The viewer is amazed at how much content pelmel full of unbelievable situations and figures was needed to convey this message.
A pair of thieves from the staff, a dog show, a charlatan from the Šumava, police arriving on a tip-off to look for "drugs" and discuss the fertilising power of bone meal - and of course, the overindulged family in the pension.
When the heroine wakes from a coma and is soon sitting at the family dinner table, made up and smoking a cigar, demanding her father's whisky and a slab of meat as a reformed vegetarian, you can't help but laugh.
On top of that, the creators explain to the viewer that "this sometimes happens after a coma."
Šajmovič's team lacks basic dramaturgical knowledge of working with a text, the ability to build up the main situations, a sense for the characters and the point, and directorial guidance.
The acting is uneven, the editing is clumsy and the overall impression is muddled.
However hard Lukáš Vaculík, Jitka Ježková or Nela Boudová try to keep their parties afloat, they have little to play for.
The only good thing about the film are the poetic shots of the Šumava nature by cameraman Vladimír Holomek and the pair of stoats.
It's not enough to sketch out a few characters, a flimsy plot, and dog puns, not to mention the more common vulgarities the characters indulge in.
Long-standing membership of the Dachshund Club - as in the case of the producer - is also not an argument.
For good intentions to promote nature and the friendship between man and dog, there must also be knowledge of the trade, if one wants to tell a believable story.
This didn't work out in this case.
There's a bit too much erotica and a minimum of feeling for the genre in this family photo.
Even as a commercial for canine therapy, this amateurish piece would not pass.
