The Middle East is experiencing unusually dry months.
Winter is the only time of the year when it rains.
"The almost total absence of rain during November, as recorded at some stations, is unusual," the Israel Meteorological Service confirms.
For example, the village of Kfar Giladi in northern Israel reported just six percent of its long-term average rainfall in November.
This week's two-day rainfall was therefore more of an exception.
It's good for us.
It hasn't rained for a long time.
It's also the right Christmas setting, said Nazareth resident Wasim Ashkar.
Rainfall in Israel comes almost exclusively in the winter months, is sporadic and irregular.
Forests rely on winter rains.
Without them, they dry out and are susceptible to fires.
It is not just about forests, but also about drinking water resources and irrigation for farmers.
The largest freshwater source in Israel, the Sea of Galilee, filled to the brim this spring, thanks to three consecutive rainy winters.
Since then the level has fallen.
Hydrologists have been warning about the drought for a long time.
"It is expected that, depending on global warming and climate change, there will be less rainfall here," said Uri Schor, a spokesman for the Israel Water Authority, in 2018.
Israel can help itself with technologies such as desalination or wastewater recycling.
The economically weaker countries, such as Lebanon, Syria and Jordan, are faring worse.
In the streets of Jordan's capital, Amman, tanker trucks are becoming more common.
Water pipes and private wells are drying up.
"This year, my orders have gone up by 70 to 80 per cent compared to the previous two years," said tanker driver Imad Suleiman in September.
Farmers clashed with security forces in the Iranian city of Isfahan.
The cause of the protests was the drought.
The bed of the local river was completely dry.
The region has experienced its driest November in many years.
