Skiers headed for the mountains at the weekend, where there was plenty of snow and good weather
The mountain resorts in the Czech Republic experienced their first major influx of skiing enthusiasts this weekend.
After heavy snowfall at the end of the working week, there is no shortage of snow and some ski resorts have opened as a result.
The skiers were not deterred by the requirement to show their covid certificate at the lifts.
While tow-bar operators are not complaining about a lack of customers, some ski equipment rental companies are reporting lower demand for their services than before the epidemic.
Thousands of people hit the running trails and ski slopes in the Liberec region over the weekend.
Today, the weather was good for skiers, with sunshine and excellent snow conditions.
"We are pleased, the opening weekend really went well from Friday evening when we had the first skiers on the hill," said Jakub Hanuš, the Director of the Ještěd Sports Area.
Hundreds of people set out for the first weekend of skiing in the new season in the Jeseník Mountains.
Open were, for example, Ski Aréna Karlov or the centre in Branná in Šumperk.
Weekend attendance was very good, with an estimated 400 people on Saturday and today.
The conditions are great.
Today the sun was shining, it was about minus three degrees, so it was perfect, said Rostislav Procházka, the representative of the ski resort in Branná.
Ski resort operators can only sell ski passes to people who are vaccinated or have recently recovered from COVID-19.
People are generally prepared for this, and they show the necessary documents, said René Hroneš from the Špindlerův Mlýn ski centre to ČTK.
"We've only seen a handful of incidents," he added.
Some rental and ski equipment shops are reporting lower demand than before the pandemic.
Fortunately, there is interest in renting skis.
It's not like in previous years, but there are still enough customers, said Alexandra Bokišová from the Opava Skiopava store.
More pressure is expected during skiing courses.
David Šinták, the manager of the Hradec Králové company Snowbear, also feels that there is not as much interest in renting ski equipment as there used to be, due to the coronavirus.
By this time before the pandemic, we were almost booked out.
Compared to the period before the pandemic, we are at around 50 percent, Šinták told ČTK.
According to him, people have become lazy during the pandemic and have learned to sit at home.
By contrast, the Novako rental agency in Boží Dar is experiencing high demand.
They started renting out skis there a week ago and interested parties now have to book them in advance.
"We start renting skis this weekend, but people have been calling in advance, so we are expecting a lot of interest, just like last year," said area manager Pavlína Nováková.
According to her, interest comparable to the period before the epidemic is also in the ski school.
