Another government ends and the law on the involvement of municipalities in the selection of a repository nowhere
Minister Karel Havlíček's proposal needs a major overhaul
The Andrej Babiš government is coming to an end and the law that was supposed to guarantee respect for the interests of municipalities and their citizens in the selection and approval of a deep geological repository for high-level radioactive waste still does not exist.
The government's legislative council suspended discussion of the proposal, which the Ministry of Industry and Trade submitted to the government after years of delays.
Its content, however, is in serious conflict not only with the affected municipalities associated in the Platform against deep storage, but also with the Association of Towns and Municipalities of the Czech Republic.
Councils are expecting a significant strengthening of their decision-making powers on storage facilities, which has been promised to mayors since 2011, when the first work on this legislation began, and which is required by the Czech atomic law and the European directive.
We expect the new government to revise the proposal in accordance with its coalition agreement, in cooperation with the municipalities.
The draft law by Minister Karel Havlíček, which is available to the Platform, is criticised by municipalities mainly for: The proposed level of involvement of municipalities and the public in the decision-making process on the selection of the site for the repository is insufficient and cannot ensure respect for the interests of municipalities and their citizens.
It can only be truly effective if the community or the public can influence whether the process goes ahead in a particular location.
This can be ensured by imposing an obligation on the Administration of Repositories to request the approval of the affected municipalities prior to the commencement of a specific procedure.
The proposed draft of the spatial plan almost completely ignores the involvement of the public and makes the citizens of the municipalities little more than mere statistics in permit proceedings.
The draft does not include the systemic setting of compensation for municipalities for the entire process of finding and selecting a site for a repository, its approval and operation.
According to today's legal rules, representatives of municipalities do not have many options to defend the interests of their citizens when looking for a place for a storage facility.
Only in some permit proceedings can they submit their comments or appeal, but it is the authority or minister in whose interest the permit is to be issued that makes the decision.
A potential lawsuit does not have a suspensive effect on the carrying out of survey or construction works.
The co-determination of self-governing bodies, which the Platform is calling for, is a principle that is commonly used in many democratically developed countries, and certainly in those that have already made progress in allowing storage, such as Sweden or Finland.
The preparation of the law is another failure of the state administration, which hires external law firms to prepare legislation.
In this case, it is a contract with the law firm HAVEL & PARTNERS s.r.o., which was signed by SÚRAO, following contracts with the lawyer Jan Zemánek.
According to the register of contracts, the total sum for this work is almost 4 million Czech crowns.
Antonín Seknička, deputy mayor of the village of Cejle in the Hrádek area and spokesman for the Platform Against Deep Geological Repository, said: After the ministers of industry, who only postponed the settlement of the position of self-governing bodies vis-à-vis state authorities in the search for a deep geological repository for highly radioactive waste to their successors, we are waiting for a more significant turnaround from the new government.
We are also offering a helping hand.
We would also like to thank the Association of Municipalities, which perceives the issue of the insufficient rights of municipalities in such a major project in a similar way as the directly affected municipalities in selected locations.
The platform against deep disposal unites 51 members (35 municipalities and cities and 16 associations) to promote a change in the state's approach to the management of spent nuclear fuel and other radioactive waste, which will not be limited to deep disposal.
The platform further argues that the decision on the choice of the location for possible storage should be subject to the prior consent of the affected municipalities.
The fear of John Goodman (69) forced him to lose weight: He lost 90 kg.
Although he didn't feel the need to change his lifestyle for years, he was eventually scared straight by doctors.
He was told he would die if he didn't lose weight.
And that took time.
Goodman has lost a total of 90 kilograms, which is half of his original weight of 180 kilograms, according to The Sun.
He revealed his new look in Los Angeles at the premiere of the animated series The Freak Brothers.
He's a totally different person from the fat guy on Roseanne!
John liked to joke that his friends and family asked him to lose weight because his large body was causing furniture to break.
"I was putting everything in my mouth," the actor said in a 2018 interview with AARP.
This time I wanted to do it slowly.
Move, exercise.
I'm at an age now where I can't afford to sit still, Mr. Goodman told ABC, whose transformation is remarkable.
Also, it depends on what kind of boss and in what context you want to use the word "boss".
If it's some text on a platform that expects readers from the gaming environment, I wouldn't translate it at all.
If it was, for example, a formal text and perhaps a university one, I would probably look for a way to describe or explain the boss.
What's more, there are different types of bosses.
For example, a game like Dark Souls has several bosses, right, and so a "boss" is like a lord/ruler of a given level, and then there's the final boss...
In many games, there are hidden bosses (super bosses, hidden bosses) that are not necessary to defeat in order to complete the game or level, but are often stronger than regular bosses.
Then there are games like Half-Life, where the bosses are there, but the player doesn't fight them directly (Tentacle, Gargantua), and can they be called bosses at all?
And then there are the mini-bosses.
To translate the word "boss" in one word is just not possible. Czech and other languages do not have a word for it (Catalan is an interesting example, which translates "boss" as the final opponent).
It's a computer-controlled opponent that is significant to the story or the game in general, stronger than all previous ones, and guarding the completion of some level or task.
