Fears for the fate of a 32-year-old Czech woman, who has been missing in Britain for several days, grew over the weekend.
Petra Srncova was last seen two weeks ago on her way home from work in the south of the British capital.
In addition to the police, her former employer and a member of parliament who represents part of London where she lived are also calling for information about the children's hospital worker.
"Petra's disappearance is completely out of character and we are becoming increasingly concerned for her welfare," said Lucy O'Connor from Lambeth Police, where Srncova worked.
"Her family in the Czech Republic is also very worried about her and just wants to know where she is," she continued.
According to her, the missing Czech woman left work at about 7:45 p.m. on Sunday, November 28, and headed home to Camberwell.
She was last seen on a bus about 30 minutes later.
Her disappearance was reported on December 3 by one of her colleagues.
According to British media, Srncová worked as an "assistant nurse" at the Evelina London Children's Hospital, which is part of the Guy's and St Thomas' NHS Foundation Trust.
"We are deeply concerned for our dear colleague Petra, who is missing," the group of medical facilities said in a tweet.
"We are appealing for anyone who may have any information which could assist in locating her to contact police," the statement continued.
